04674nam a22006375i 9781787446755DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874467557 a10.1515/97817874467552doi  a(DE-B1597)675117  a(OCoLC)1420506817  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a833/.9122231 aMehigan, Tim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRobert Musil and the Question of Science :bEthics, Aesthetics, and the Problem of the Two Cultures /cTim Mehigan.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2020] 1bCamden House, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (180 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v20800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Musil’s Intellectual Position -- tPart I. Musil and the Two Cultures -- t1: The Question of Science -- t2: Musil, Ernst Mach, and the Problem of Causality -- t3: Musil’s Theory of Vision -- t4: The Essays -- tPart II. Aesthetics and Ethics in the Context of the Two Cultures -- t5: Modernity’s Crisis -- t6: Musil’s Concept of Value -- t7: Unions: “An Episode of More than Merely Personal Significance” -- t8: The Problem of Trust in The Man Without Qualities -- t9: Musil’s Correspondence Project: The Man Without Qualities and The Blackbird -- tConclusion: “A General Secretariat of Precision and Soul”: Ethics, Knowledge, and Literature after the Fourth Revolution -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA major new study of Robert Musil by one of the world's leading Musil scholars. Musil's extraordinary works, the study reveals, emerged from the problem of the "two cultures."The modern era is marked by the separate life of two cultures of understanding, one derived from art and its discourses, the other from science and its practices. This "problem of the two cultures" (as coined by C.P. Snow) describes the difficulty of bringing these distinct ways of understanding the world together. The works of the Austrian author Robert Musil (1930-33) represent the most distinguished treatment of this problem in the modern era. Nevertheless, doubts persist about Musil's true intentions. Did he maintain that the separation between art and science could be resolved? Or did he rise above the problem by advocating a new order of being or "other condition" that would dispense with it altogether? Mehigan's study moves these questions to center stage. He lends new clarity to the debate about Musil's position in regard to the two cultures by shining a light on ethical questions the author ultimately wished to clarify. It is the shape of a hard-won ethics, Mehigan argues, that provides the key to an effective response to the problem of the two cultures - an ethics, in the end, that can only be put forward as a new kind of art. Tim Mehigan is Professor of German and Deputy Director of the Institute for Advanced Studies in the Humanities at the University of Queensland, Australia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGerman History. 4aGerman Literature. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aArt.  aCultural Intersection.  aLiterature.  aModern Era.  aPhilosophy.  aRobert Musil.  aScience and Ethics.  aTwo Cultures Problem.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446755?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446755/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Packa